# servers.config — dolr-ai Hetzner infrastructure (SHARED across all services)
#
# This file holds infrastructure-wide values that are the SAME for every
# dolr-ai service deployed to the Hetzner cluster. Unlike project.config
# (which is per-project), servers.config almost never changes.
#
# WHEN to update this file:
#   - Saikat replaces a server (IP changes)
#   - We add a 4th server to the cluster
#   - We rotate the CI SSH key (key fingerprint stays the same; only the
#     value of the GitHub Secret changes)
#
# Sourced by:
#   - scripts/ci/deploy-db-stack.sh and scripts/ci/deploy-app.sh (on the server)
#   - .github/workflows/deploy.yml (parsed into $GITHUB_ENV)
#
# WHY checked into the repo (not GitHub Secrets)?
# IPs and the deploy username are NOT secrets. They're public knowledge for
# anyone with access to the repo. Putting them in GitHub Secrets means every
# new project repo has to set the same 4 secrets again — fragile and
# error-prone. Checking them in means new projects "just work" with no
# secret-setup ceremony for these values.
#
# WHAT IS still a secret (and therefore in GitHub Secrets, not here):
#   - HETZNER_BARE_METAL_GITHUB_ACTIONS_SSH_PRIVATE_KEY (the actual key)
#   - POSTGRES_PASSWORD, REPLICATION_PASSWORD
#   - DATABASE_URL_SERVER_1, DATABASE_URL_SERVER_2
#   - SENTRY_DSN

# ----- Hetzner servers -----
# rishi-1 = Swarm manager + app + DB + Caddy
# rishi-2 = Swarm worker + app + DB + Caddy
# rishi-3 = Swarm worker + DB + self-hosted Sentry + Caddy (no app — its
#           Caddy proxies to rishi-1/rishi-2 over the swarm overlay).
# Cloudflare wildcard `*.rishi.yral.com` round-robins to all THREE IPs,
# so every host needs Caddy listening on 443 to avoid 521s. rishi-3 was
# added to that wildcard by Saikat; until 2026-05-03 it had no Caddy and
# silently dropped 1-in-3 Cloudflare probes.
SERVER_1_IP=138.201.137.181
SERVER_2_IP=136.243.150.84
SERVER_3_IP=136.243.147.225

# ----- App servers (subset of the cluster that runs the application) -----
# rishi-1 and rishi-2 run the app container. This list drives:
#   1) Which hosts the CI deploy-app job iterates over (image pull,
#      container start, health check).
#   2) The upstream list inside the Caddy snippet — every entry becomes
#      a `reverse_proxy` upstream for Caddy on every CADDY_HOST, so
#      Caddy on any host can fail over to any healthy app replica.
# Comma-separated, no spaces. To promote rishi-3 to an app server, append it
# here AND to CADDY_HOSTS below (it is already in CADDY_HOSTS).
APP_SERVERS=rishi-1,rishi-2

# ----- Caddy hosts (every server that listens on :443 for users) -----
# Must include every IP listed in the Cloudflare wildcard `*.rishi`
# DNS record, otherwise the missing host silently drops Cloudflare probes
# and surfaces as 521 on Uptime Kuma. CI pushes Caddy snippets to every
# host listed here:
#   - APP_SERVERS get their snippets via scripts/ci/deploy-app.sh
#     (which deploys the app container + writes the snippet in one go).
#   - The remaining CADDY_HOSTS get just the snippet via
#     scripts/ci/update-caddy-snippet.sh (no app deploy on these).
# Comma-separated, no spaces. SUPERSET of APP_SERVERS.
CADDY_HOSTS=rishi-1,rishi-2,rishi-3

# ----- Deploy user (non-root) -----
# Every CI deploy uses this user. We deliberately do NOT have root SSH for
# day-to-day deploys. Root is needed only ONCE per server for swarm-setup.sh
# (opening UFW ports + initializing Swarm). After that, root is never needed.
DEPLOY_USER=deploy

# ----- Local CI key path -----
# Where to find the CI SSH private key on a developer's Mac. The actual key
# is also stored as a GitHub Secret named HETZNER_BARE_METAL_GITHUB_ACTIONS_SSH_PRIVATE_KEY.
# Used by local helper scripts (e.g. tests/test_local_stack.sh) and by
# `bash scripts/ssh-deploy.sh rishi-1` if we add such a helper.
SSH_KEY_PATH=~/.ssh/rishi-hetzner-ci-key
